{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"37296eca-5d5b-4a7f-99ed-dd23a5ed15e4","content":"Good news — `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` **still exist** on MAUI's `Application` class, so your overrides will compile and work as-is.\n\nHowever, MAUI also introduces **Window-level lifecycle events**, which are more granular and the recommended approach going forward. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class to return a custom `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n\n        window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart  */ };\n        window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep  */ };\n        window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n        window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* app teardown     */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` |\n| *(none)* | `Window.Destroying` |\n\nMAUI also adds `Activated`, `Deactivated`, and `Backgrounding` events for finer control. For platform-specific hooks, see `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bdd3db06-c9a8-4dca-8cae-029d5eb78d42","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`. But more directly, the `Window` class has equivalent methods:\n\n- `Window.Created` / `OnCreated()` \n\n\n- `Window.Stopped` / `OnStopped()`\n- `Window.Resumed` / `OnResumed()`\n- `Window.Destroying` / `OnDestroying()`\n\nIn .NET MAUI, you can either create a custom Window subclass and override these lifecycle methods directly, or subscribe to the lifecycle events instead.\n\nActually, I should clarify — the `Application` class still has `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` methods, so the migration path is pretty straightforward. But the newer, more granular approach is to use the Window-level lifecycle events instead.","outputTokens":1046},"id":"6223aecf-1c20-4a28-a816-311c12aa1e33","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:46:31.771Z","parentId":"3b374a44-15b5-403b-8e51-f5c3e4a60c43"}
